ar cells","Chief cells","Oxyphil cells","Delta cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular cells\u003C/strong\u003E of the thyroid gland synthesize thyroglobulin in their endoplasmic reticulum. The protein is then transported to the Golgi apparatus for glycosylation before being packaged into vesicles and secreted into the follicular lumen where iodination occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParafollicular cells\u003C/strong\u003E (C cells) are found in the thyroid gland but produce calcitonin, not thyroglobulin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChief cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the parathyroid glands and produce parathyroid hormone\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxyphil cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the parathyroid glands but their function remains unclear\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelta cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the pancreatic islets and produce somatostatin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter iodination in the follicular lumen, thyroglobulin serves as the storage form of thyroid hormones within the colloid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyroid follicular cells synthesize thyroglobulin in the endoplasmic reticulum before iodination and storage in follicular colloid","Thyroglobulin is the precursor protein for thyroid hormones T3 and T4","The thyroid gland contains two main cell types: follicular cells that produce thyroid hormones and parafollicular cells that produce calcitonin"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Indrasena BS. Use of thyroglobulin as a tumour marker. World J Biol Chem. 2017 Feb 26;8(1):81-85. doi: 10.4331/wjbc.v8.i1.81. PMID: 28289520; PMCID: 